     //some base types which we build the components on, since they all have simulair structure:
     // * A component class encapsulating the needed stuff
     // * mostly one Tsynaclient class encapsulating some method
     // * A thread to handle some synchronized methods
     //The thread and the component share some behaviour, events are generated by synchronized thread methods.
     //TVisual synapse is not a asynchronous library, but partly behaves that way.

     //from the base TVirtualSynapse class, we can derive the protocol implementations.
     //This way TDNSSend, THTTPSend, TFTPSend, TTCPBlockSocket, TUDPBlockSocket and a TCP server.
     //other protocols like POP3 and IMAP can be done, but one strongly must consider how to implement this.
     //In fact, i would favorize using a self-written thread for such implementations.
     //MIME related stuff does not have to get encapsulated by a component.
     //a sendmail component would be nice.
     //added is the ip helper.

     //Notes:
     //TIPHelper will only work on windows 2000 and higher, maybe windows ME.
     //it will not work on linux either.
     //if only DNS servers are needed, try synapse getDNSservers function.
     //Todo: make TIPHelper cross/multi platform.

     //todo:
     //optionally, we can gain performance by creating multiple threads per
     //component, but this makes things some more complex (but not that much)
     //for visualhttp or visualdns this could be quite handy.

     //todo:
     //add a socket hook with onstatus.
     //this is fun, because it interferes with above multi-threaded todo thingie.
     //so, we need some kind of uniform handle. problem is: which? threads get re-used.
     //so, in fact i would suggest some kind of unique handle when things are added to the queue.
     //now, one can abort a connection by handle, gets a handle with an onprogress etc.
     //todo: think about this issue.
     //fix: generate a job id. this conforms with the uniform enqueue command.

     //now added socks support
     //there is some issue on this: thread only gets info when created.
     //no mechanism yet to inform thread of changes.

     //other thing is abort method. this is supported by most methods,
     //and could be called in the call back procedures.
     //a uniform mechanism could exist in the callback procedures,
     //if one would set the abort property.

     //however, this must be placed outside synchronized routine
     //because of new callbacks when done this.

     //issues on the continue:
     //UDP port looses bind... protocols like httpsend and udpsend will recreate socket when needed.

const MAX_REDIRECT_COUNT = 12;

type //we have to re-type some stuff for the callback methods, else clients
     //have to include corresponding units:
    THookReason = type THookSocketReason;
    TSynapseSocket = type TSocksBlockSocket;
{
hookreasons are:
    HR_ResolvingBegin,
    HR_ResolvingEnd,
    HR_SocketCreate,
    HR_SocketClose,
    HR_Bind,
    HR_Connect,
    HR_CanRead,
    HR_CanWrite,
    HR_Listen,
    HR_Accept,
    HR_ReadCount,
    HR_WriteCount,
    HR_Wait,
    HR_Error
}
    THostInfo = record
      Host: String;
      Port: String;
